\section{The Post-Web Claim}

Kapnet is post-web only in a precise sense. It is not post-web because it abandons pages, links, profiles, comments, feeds, search, dashboards, forums, or collaborative documents. Those forms are too useful to discard. Kapnet is post-web because it refuses the old bargain in which platforms provided convenience in exchange for opacity, capture, behavioral extraction, unforkable identity, and hidden ranking authority.

The post-web move is to retain familiar affordances while relocating authority. The page is no longer platform-hosted content. It is a rendered object. The feed is no longer an opaque behavioral product. It is a declared braid projection. The profile is no longer an account page. It is an identity render. The search engine is no longer a private ranking oracle. It is a scoped retrieval policy. The forum is no longer a server-owned discussion board. It is a room with visible governance. The app store is no longer a platform gate. It is a Kapplet registry under KOR review.

This lets Kapnet meet users where they are while changing what the interface means. It is not enough for a Kapnet interface to look like the web. It must behave with Kapnet semantics underneath. Otherwise it is merely another skin on platform logic.

\section{Conclusion}

Kapnet's adjacent protocol ecology should be read as a ladder of encapsulation rather than a set of integrations. Bitcoin supplies the reference physics. Transport systems move messages. Meshes replicate local state. Editors and chats host pre-public collaboration. Content-addressed stores carry bodies. Social protocols circulate events. Identity systems address actors. Workflow engines recover long processes. Game engines model deterministic rule spaces. Web patterns provide familiar affordances. LLM sessions generate Kapactive material.

Kapnet's task is to decide when and how any of this becomes a governed object.

The decisive transformation is not storage, not encryption, not replication, not federation, not content addressing, and not interface familiarity. Those are necessary but insufficient. The decisive transformation is the crossing into TXXM objecthood under KOR scope, with deterministic render, capability context, economic posture, replayable history, and an intelligible path toward braid and knot memory.

Kapnet therefore does not replace the web by erasing it. It metabolizes the web. It does not replace adjacent protocols by swallowing them whole. It encapsulates them according to level, purpose, and consequence. It does not make every activity public. It gives activity a gradient: private work, local kapcompute, federated replication, canonical objecthood, public braid, knot memory, and timechain legibility.

That is the heart of the synthesis. Kapnet is the membrane by which ordinary digital activity becomes cyberphysical discourse: authored, scoped, priced, rendered, governed, replayable, forkable, and remembered.
